@bendyer Check this out: https://github.com/PX4/Firmware/blob/master/src/modules/uavcan/uavcan_servers.cpp#L524-L527:

``` c++
                switch (command_id) {
                case 1: {
                        // Param save request
                        _param_save_opcode = uavcan::protocol::param::ExecuteOpcode::Request::OPCODE_SAVE;
                        param_opcode(get_next_dirty_node_id(1));
                        break;
                    }
                case 2: {
                        // Command is a param erase request -- apply it to all active nodes by setting the dirty bit
                        _param_save_opcode = uavcan::protocol::param::ExecuteOpcode::Request::OPCODE_ERASE;
                        for (int i = 1; i < 128; i = get_next_active_node_id(i)) {
                            set_node_params_dirty(i);
                        }
                        param_opcode(get_next_dirty_node_id(1));
                        break;
                    }
                }
```

In the case 1, the call to `param_opcode()` will fail with an error report to CLI if there's no dirty nodes present. The error report looks like this:

```
uavcan fw srv: UAVCAN command bridge: couldn't send ExecuteOpcode: -2
```

Error code -2 means [`ErrInvalidParam`](https://github.com/UAVCAN/libuavcan/blob/master/libuavcan/include/uavcan/error.hpp#L26), since the server is trying to call the service on node ID 128, which is not valid.

Currently, if a node that does not implement configuration services is connected to the bus, the UAVCAN parameter bridge causes QGC to display a scary error box saying that it could not retrieve parameters and that the reason is probably a problem in the firmware.

The UAVCAN parameter bridge should detect nodes that do not implement configuration services and simply ignore them. The simplest way to handle it is to just give up retrieving parameters after the first unsuccessful attempt.

